        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-secondary">8. Emotional Intelligence</h1>
        <p class="text-lg italic text-primary/80">"Think about feelings"</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        People will forget what you said, they'll forget what you did, but they'll never forget how you made them feel. 
        This principle transcends mere politeness or social convention—it's about understanding that human beings are 
        fundamentally emotional creatures who make decisions based on how they feel, then rationalize those decisions 
        afterward. Master this understanding, and you'll navigate relationships, negotiations, and conflicts with 
        unprecedented effectiveness.
      </p>
      
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Emotional Economics</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Every interaction creates an emotional transaction. You either deposit positive feelings (making someone feel 
        heard, valued, respected, or capable) or withdraw them (making someone feel dismissed, incompetent, irrelevant, 
        or attacked). These emotional accounts compound over time. People with positive balances become allies, 
        advocates, and resources. Those with negative balances become obstacles, enemies, or, at best, reluctant 
        participants in your success.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        The most successful people aren't necessarily the smartest or most talented—they're the ones who consistently 
        make others feel good about themselves. They understand that emotional state affects performance, decision-making, 
        and cooperation. A person who feels valued and respected will go out of their way to help you succeed. Someone 
        who feels diminished or ignored will find reasons to see you fail.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-primary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-secondary/20 backdrop-blur-sm mb-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-3">The Four Emotional Fundamentals:</h4>
        <ul class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li>• <strong class="text-secondary">Recognition:</strong> Make people feel seen and acknowledged</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-secondary">Competence:</strong> Help people feel capable and intelligent</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-secondary">Importance:</strong> Demonstrate that their opinions and contributions matter</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-secondary">Safety:</strong> Create environments where people can be authentic without fear</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Case Study: The Meeting That Changed Everything</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Sarah is a project manager leading a team through a difficult product launch. One team member, David, has been 
        struggling with his components and is visibly stressed during team meetings. He rarely speaks up and seems 
        withdrawn. Most managers would either ignore this (focusing only on deliverables) or address it directly 
        (which often feels like criticism).
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Sarah's Approach:</strong> Instead of calling David out publicly or ignoring his struggle, Sarah 
        schedules a private conversation. She starts by acknowledging his expertise: "I know you've solved complex 
        problems like this before." She validates his feelings: "This timeline is genuinely challenging—you're not 
        imagining it." Then she collaborates on solutions: "What would help you feel more confident about hitting 
        our milestones?"
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Transformation:</strong> David doesn't just improve his performance—he becomes one of Sarah's 
        strongest advocates. When senior leadership questions the project timeline, David speaks up to defend the 
        team's approach. When other departments need technical consultation, he specifically recommends Sarah's 
        expertise. The emotional investment Sarah made compounds into professional capital that serves her for years.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Daily Practice</h3>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Morning Check-in</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Before important interactions, ask: "How do I want this person to feel after our conversation?" Plan specific actions to create that feeling.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-primary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">Active Observation</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Notice body language, tone changes, and energy shifts. People telegraph their emotional state constantly—most just aren't paying attention.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-primary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">Emotional Reflection</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">After difficult conversations, ask: "How did that person feel when we finished?" If you can't answer confidently, you weren't paying attention.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Strategic Empathy</h4>
          <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">Before criticizing or correcting someone, find something genuine to appreciate first. Lead with deposits before making withdrawals.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Advanced Emotional Strategies</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Emotional Jujitsu:</strong> When someone is angry or defensive, resist the urge to defend yourself 
        or match their energy. Instead, reflect their underlying emotion: "I can see this is really frustrating for you. 
        Help me understand what's most important here." This validates their feeling while redirecting toward solutions.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Status Elevation:</strong> Most people feel diminished in their daily lives—overlooked, undervalued, 
        or taken for granted. Look for opportunities to make others feel important. Ask for their opinion on something 
        outside their expertise. Thank them publicly for contributions others might miss. Reference their past successes 
        when introducing them to others.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Emotional Memory Bank:</strong> Remember what matters to people beyond work—their children's names, 
        their hobbies, their concerns. When you demonstrate that they exist in your mind as complete human beings rather 
        than functional roles, you create profound connection. People will move mountains for those who see them as whole persons.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Musical Illustration: "The Way You Make Me Feel"</h3>
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-primary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-secondary/20 backdrop-blur-sm mb-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
          <span class="icon-[tabler--music] size-6 text-secondary"></span>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary">Michael Jackson - "The Way You Make Me Feel"</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-base-content/60">The ultimate song about emotional impact and connection</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          Michael Jackson's masterpiece captures the essence of emotional intelligence perfectly. The song is entirely 
          focused on the emotional experience he creates for another person—the joy, excitement, and positive feelings 
          his presence generates. This is emotional intelligence in action: being deeply aware of and intentional about 
          the emotional impact you have on others.
        </p>
        <p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Notice how the song doesn't focus on what he wants or needs, but on the experience he creates. That's the 
          mindset shift: from "what can I get?" to "what can I give emotionally?"
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Practical Applications</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>In Conflict Resolution:</strong> Focus on making both parties feel heard before attempting solutions. 
        "Let me make sure I understand your perspective..." creates safety and demonstrates respect for their position.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>In Leadership:</strong> Catch people doing things right and acknowledge it specifically. "I noticed 
        how you handled that client concern—the way you listened first before offering solutions showed real professionalism."
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>In Negotiations:</strong> Help the other party feel smart and capable throughout the process. "That's 
        a really good point—I hadn't considered that angle." When people feel respected and intelligent, they're more 
        likely to respect your position in return.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-secondary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-primary/20 backdrop-blur-sm">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-3">Warning Signs You're Emotionally Tone-Deaf:</h4>
        <ul class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">People often seem defensive around you</strong> without clear reason</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">Your "helpful" suggestions are frequently rejected</strong> even when they're objectively good</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">Conversations end abruptly</strong> or people find excuses to leave</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">You're surprised when people are upset</strong> by things you said or did</li>
          <li>• <strong class="text-primary">People don't share personal information</strong> or ask for your advice</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
